{Another possible plan is to consolidate the control over c4 with ...b7-b5.
The success of this operation greatly depends on whether Black succeeds in
playing ...a6-a5 followed by either ...a5-a4 or ...axb4. This would turn the
a3- or b4 pawns into permanent weaknesses. If White is quicker in advancing
his pawn to a5, then a6 would be a chronic weakness, especially dangerous for
Black in the endgame. Next we will see a practical example in which Black
managed to stabilize the queenside without making any commitments at all.}  *

