1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 ({We do not have this
concrete position in our repertoire, as White usually exchanges on d5 later
than in this game.} 5... Be7) 6. Qc2 Na6 {In our repertoire, we refrain from
this manoeuvre, but the position is slightly different there with Bg5 and ...
Be7 on board. In that case, White can play e2-e3, when after ...Nb4 the knight
would soon have to return. With the bishop on c1, e2-e3 is not a serious
option.} 7. a3 Nc7 8. Bg5 g6 $1 {We have this plan at several points in our
repertoire. Black prepares ...Bf5.} 9. e3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Be7 12. O-O
O-O 13. b4 {Even in the absence of the light-squared bishops, the minority
attack can be consistent. Strictly speaking, Black has gained a tempo with his
knight manoeuvre, as a2-a3 will not be very useful after ...a7-a6, when White
has to spend time on a3-a4 to prepare b4-b5. But on the other hand, the knight
on c7 fulfils a purely defensive task at this point, by just controlling b5
and being far away from c4 or even b6.} Ne4 {The correct decision, aiming to
exchange the knight on c3 and thus slow down b4-b5.} 14. Bf4 {Portisch rightly
decides to target the knight on c7, in order to keep his main plan possible.} (
{If} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Rfb1 {Precisely this rook, in anticipation of ...a7-a5.}
Nd6 16. a4 a6 {Now is the right moment to mention that in the Carlsbad
structure d6 is the optimal square for the knight. It controls c4 and e4 while
also taking measures against b4-b5. More about it later in the game. White
does not have any constructive plans while Black can prepare the same kind of
kingside expansion as in the game.} 17. Nd2 Rae8 18. Nb3 {, trying to
reinforce the queenside pressure (although this has no practical effects),
Black can even speed up his attack with 18...f5!? as the knight is far from e5.
} f5 $5 {as the knight is far from e5.}) 14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 $6 {Rather
inconsequent.} ({White should have carried out his plan until its logical end
with} 15. Bxc7 $1 Qxc7 16. Qxc3 {, keeping his queenside attack alive. A
possible continuation is} a6 17. a4 Rfc8 18. Rab1 Bd6 19. Rfc1 Kg7 20. Qb3 {
With b4-b5 in the air, Black should stabilize the queenside with} a5 $5 21. b5
(21. bxa5 Rcb8 $15 {leaves White with weaknesses.}) 21... Rab8 {with static
equality, since} 22. bxc6 bxc6 23. Qc2 Rb4 {would offer Black certain
counterplay. This is another structure to remember. The presence of the
a-pawns helps Black.}) 15... Bd6 {Black uses the given chance to keep his
knight. When agreeing to that, Portisch must have thought that the knight is
passive on c7, overlooking a small tactical detail.} 16. Bxd6 $6 {Going all
the way.} ({Better was} 16. a4 Bxf4 ({If} 16... Ne8 {Black cannot bring his
knight to d6 in time to stop} 17. b5) 17. exf4 $11 {True, White's structure is
imperfect, but he is safe against any kingside attack. He could play Ne5 and
if ...f7-f6, then Nd3.}) 16... Nb5 $1 {The move missed by Portisch. The knight
reaches d6 in time.} 17. Qb3 Nxd6 $15 {Black has achieved a dream position.
The knight on d6 controls all important squares and Black is ready to launch a
slow positional attack based on ...f7-f6, ...g6-g5 and ...h7-h5-h4.} 18. a4 a6
19. Ne5 {White will play without a plan until the end of the game. о /\} ({
Preparing b4-b5 is not easy, but it was all White had to put up at least some
resistance. Here is an illustrative line based on transferring the knight to
c3:} 19. Nd2 Qe7 20. Nb1 a5 $5 {A logical counterplay, taking advantage of
White's temporary lack of coordination.} 21. b5 cxb5 22. axb5 (22. Qxd5 b4 $17
{followed by ...b7-b5 soon creates two dangerous queenside passers.}) 22... Nc4
23. Rc1 Rfc8 24. Nc3 Qb4 $5 (24... Nxe3 25. fxe3 Qxe3+ 26. Kh1 Rc4 {offers
Black good compensation for the knight, but hardly an advantage.}) 25. Qa2 ({
Relatively best.} 25. Rab1 $2 {loses to} Nd2 26. Qxb4 axb4 27. Rxb4 Rxc3 $1) ({
Or if} 25. Qxb4 axb4 26. Nxd5 b3 $1 $17 {and the b-pawn is very unpleasant.
For instance} 27. Ne7+ $2 Kf8 28. Nxc8 b2 $1 {wins a knight.}) 25... Nxe3 26.
Nxd5 Rxc1+ 27. Rxc1 Nxd5 28. Qxd5 Qa3 $5 29. Rf1 Qe7 {Black's position remains
preferable because of his outside passed pawn, but White is still very much in
the game.}) 19... Re8 20. Rfe1 Qg5 21. h3 Kg7 22. Qc2 Re6 23. Rac1 Rae8 24. Qb1
Qh5 $1 25. Qb3 f6 26. Nd3 g5 27. Qd1 Qg6 28. Qc2 R6e7 29. Red1 h5 30. Qb1 ({
Now or at later moments White could have considered 30.Nc5, to offer the queen
exchange before Black's kingside pressure becomes too strong.} 30. Nc5 {
to offer the queen exchange before Black's kingside pressure becomes too
strong.}) 30... h4 {Black has carried out his plan with brilliant consequence,
while White has been mainly waiting.} 31. Qc2 {о /\} g4 $6 {This premature
break will be crowned by success only because of White's lack of resolution.} (
{Black should have prepared it with} 31... Kh6 $5 {planning to transfer his
rooks to the g-file.} 32. Kh2 ({The attempt at evacuation} 32. Kf1 {can be met
with} Nc4 {threatening ...Rxe3.}) 32... Rg7 33. Rg1 Reg8 34. Nc5 Qxc2 35. Rxc2
f5 36. Nd3 g4 37. hxg4 fxg4 38. Rh1 Kg5 $15 {, with a very unpleasant position
for White.}) 32. Nf4 $2 ({Hard to say why Portisch refrained from stabilizing
his position with} 32. hxg4 Qxg4 33. Nf4 {The only active attempt is} h3 $5 34.
Nxh3 Nf5 35. Nf4 Re4 ({Preparing ...Nh4 followed by ...Rxf4} 35... Nh4 {
is ineffective due to} 36. Kf1) 36. f3 Nxe3 37. Qxe4 Rxe4 38. fxg4 Nxd1 39.
Nh5+ Kg6 40. Rxd1 Rxg4 41. Nxf6 Kxf6 42. Kf2 {and White should reach a draw
with a well-timed b4-b5 (finally possible!).}) 32... Qxc2 33. Rxc2 g3 $1 {
о /\The weakness on e3 is decisive.} 34. Rd3 (34. fxg3 Nf5 $1 $19) 34... Kh6
35. Kf1 Kg5 36. Ne2 Nc4 37. Rcc3 Nb2 38. Rd2 Nxa4 39. Rb3 Nb6 40. Ng1 Nc4 41.
Nf3+ Kh5 42. Rdd3 a5 $1 43. bxa5 Ra8 44. Rd1 Rxa5 45. Re1 b5 46. Re2 Ra1+ 47.
Re1 Rea7 48. fxg3 Rxe1+ (48... hxg3 $19) 49. Kxe1 Ra1+ 50. Ke2 hxg3 51. Ne1
Ra2+ 52. Kd1 Rd2+ 53. Kc1 Re2 54. Kd1 Rxe3 55. Rxe3 Nxe3+ 56. Ke2 Nf5 57. Nc2
Nh4 58. Nb4 Nxg2 59. Kf3 Nh4+ 60. Kxg3 Nf5+ 61. Kf4 Nxd4 62. Ke3 Nf5+ 0-1

