{The next example features the second typical situation for our repertoire,
involving an early Bxf6.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 ({
A more natural move order is} 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. cxd5 exd5) 5... exd5 6.
Bg5 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 Re8 {This move is probably aimed at
inhibiting e3-e4 before making any queenside commitments.} ({When Black has
the bishops' pair he has a wider choice with respect to the way of meeting or
anticipating the minority attack. We are familiar already with} 9... c6 10. O-O
Nd7 11. b4 a6 12. a4 Nb6) 10. O-O {о /\} a5 ({Even after spending a tempo on ..
.Re8 Black would be in time to switch to the aforementioned plan:} 10... c6 11.
b4 a6 12. a4 Nd7 13. b5 {Otherwise ...Nb6.} Nc5 $5 14. Bc2 (14. Be2 {even
hands over the initiative:} Ne4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Nd2 c5 $15) 14... Ne6 15.
bxc6 bxc6 {Threatening ...c6-c5.} 16. Qd2 a5 $5 {Black has reached a more
active version of the structure mentioned in the comments to White's 15th move
in the previous game. He plans ...Ba6, ..Rb8, ...Qd6 and keeps ...c6-c5 in
reserve. In this line we can feel the latent force of the bishop on f6.}) 11.
h3 {It will later turn out that this prophylactic move weakens the kingside.} (
{I assume that White wanted to stabilize his knight on f3, as if} 11. Qc2 Na6 (
11... Bg4 $2 12. Qb3 {loses a pawn.}) 12. a3 Bg4 13. Nd2 {Black has} c5 {
with excellent counterplay, for instance} 14. h3 cxd4 15. exd4 Be6 {, reaching
a structure that is familiar to us from the previous strategic article.}) 11...
c6 {о /\} 12. Rc1 {White plays without a clear plan.} ({Under the given
circumstances, continuing the minority attack would mainly cause weaknesses in
the own camp:} 12. a3 Nd7 13. b4 b5 {This is possible only with the insertion
of a7-a5 and a2-a3. Otherwise, White would break with a2-a4.} 14. Qc2 ({
More active is} 14. e4 {when Black's most solid plan is} Nb6 15. e5 Be7 16. Qb3
Bf8 17. Ne2 Nc4 18. Nf4 Re7 19. Bc2 g6 $5 {, preparing to meet Bd3 with ...Bf5
and keeping the possibility of taking control over the a-file with Rea7.})
14... Nb6 15. Nd2 axb4 16. axb4 Rxa1 17. Rxa1 Qd6 {In the absence of the white
dark-squared bishop, the pawn on b4 is chronically weak.} 18. Na2 Nc4 19. Bxc4
bxc4 20. Qa4 Bd7 21. Rc1 Rb8 22. Nb1 g5 {With the queenside stable, Black is
ready for his kingside attack.} 23. Nbc3 h5 24. Qd1 g4 $17 {Lan,Z (2354)-Ma,Q 
(2637) Beijing 2017 (0-1, 52)}) ({White should adopt a neutral policy for the
time being, keeping the possibility of e3-e4.} 12. Qc2 Nd7 13. Rfe1 Nf8 $5 ({
Slightly more ambitious than} 13... Nb6 {, when White could try} 14. e4 dxe4
15. Nxe4 Nd5 16. a3 Be7 {with approximate equality, as White's activity
compensates for the weakness of the isolani.}) 14. a3 ({Now that the knight is
far away from c4, this plan is more adequate.} 14. e4 Ne6 {could lead to a
structure examined in the previous strategic article.}) 14... Ne6 15. b4 Qd6
16. b5 ({White should not delay concrete action as if} 16. Qb3 {Black can
start a slow but consistent kingside attack:} Ng5 17. Nxg5 hxg5 18. b5 g6 19.
Na4 g4 20. hxg4 Bxg4 21. bxc6 bxc6 22. Nc5 Kg7) 16... c5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Rad1
Be6 {Once again, the structure resembles those examined in the previous
article.}) 12... Nd7 13. Na4 Be7 14. Qb3 Bd6 15. Nc5 Rb8 {о /\White's
queenside pressure is sterile.} 16. Nxd7 $6 {This only helps Black completing
his development after having wasted a lot of time on a pseudo-attack.} ({
But Black has excellent play after, say} 16. Qc2 Qf6 {as if} 17. e4 $6 Bxc5 18.
dxc5 dxe4 19. Bxe4 Nxc5 $1 {Black wins a pawn, for instance} 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21.
Qxc5 Rxb2 22. Qxa5 Bxh3 $17) 16... Bxd7 17. Qc2 Qf6 18. Qe2 Re7 19. Rfe1 Rbe8 {
о /\Black's perfect regrouping is very aesthetically pleasing. I would make a
special mention about the bishops, who control both wings. Without promising
pawn breaks in view, White is doomed to passivity.} 20. Nd2 g6 21. a3 h5 22.
Qf3 (22. Rb1 Kg7 23. b4 axb4 24. axb4 b5 {does not improve things for White.
While sustaining the attack, the bishops defend c6 and keep b4 under pressure.}
) 22... Qg5 23. Nf1 Kg7 24. Nh2 h4 25. Rcd1 f5 {After Black has started to
advance his pawns, the rest is agony.} 26. Nf1 Qf6 27. Qe2 g5 28. Qd2 g4 29.
Kh1 f4 30. hxg4 Bxg4 31. f3 Bd7 32. Bc2 fxe3 33. Rxe3 Rxe3 34. Nxe3 h3 35. Qf2
Qf4 36. Nf1 Bg4 37. Kg1 hxg2 38. Kxg2 Rf8 39. Rd3 Bf5 40. Rc3 Bxc2 41. Qxc2
Qxd4 42. Rb3 Rf7 43. Qf2 Qf6 44. Ne3 Qf4 45. Ng4 d4 46. Rd3 c5 47. a4 Qf5 48.
Rd1 Re7 49. Qd2 Bf4 50. Qf2 d3 51. Re1 Qg5 52. Kf1 d2 0-1

