{[#]White has won a pawn, but otherwise his queenside attack has not even
started. Besides, his knight is completely out of play. How can Black make use
of his kingside pressure?} 29... Nxf2 $1 {A winning combination. Since the
white knight does not count for practical reasons, this should not even be
considered a sacrifice.} (29... Nf6 {allows White to neutralize the pressure
with} 30. Qd1 $1 Qf5 31. Qf3 Qg6 32. Rf1 $5 {taking measures against ...Ne4
followed by ...Rf6.}) 30. Qxf2 {No matter how White takes on f2, he will not
find safe squares for his king and queen, as his rooks are a bit far from the
kingside, too.} ({If} 30. Kxf2 Rf6+ 31. Kg2 Qf3+ 32. Kh2 Rxe3 $19) 30... Rf6
31. Qg1 (31. Qd2 Qf3+ 32. Kh2 Rxe3 33. Re1 Qxg3+ 34. Kh1 Rxe1+ 35. Rxe1 Rg6 {
, threatening ...Bh3+ and mating soon.}) 31... Qe2+ 32. Kh1 Rf2 {[%cal Ge2f3]
With the imparable threat ...Qf3+. 0-1 Fuster,G-Simagin,V Telegraph 1949} *

