1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 {In the late seventies and
early eighties, Kortschnoj was one of the few pioneers trying to create
problems in this system for Black, mainly in his matches with Karpov. Nowadays,
this line is not a bit less important than 5.Bg5. On f4, the bishop does not
put immediate pressure on Black's centre (in other words, it does not
undermine his control on d5). but since this is an open invitation for Black
to play an early ...c7-c5, the bishop is likely to restrict Black's mobility
by controlling a few important squares along the h2-b8 diagonal.} (5. g3 {
is a somewhat unusual way of transposing to the Catalan.}) 5... O-O 6. e3 ({
As far as I understand,} 6. a3 {is an attempt to transpose to some of the 6.e3
c5 lines and avoid some black deviations. But it does not cross our plans as
a2-a3 is not very useful in the positions with hanging pawns. (Please refer to
our main lines below).} b6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 (7... exd5 {is also possible. If 8.e3,
a2-a3 is mainly a waste of time, while after} 8. g3 c5 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. O-O Na6 {
play transposes to an a2-a3 Queen's Indian. This will be examined in the third
database, dedicated to the Catalan and the Reti systems.}) 8. Nxd5 exd5 ({
With a2-a3 on the board, I find this best. But} 8... Qxd5 {is also playable:}
9. Bxc7 Ba6 10. Bxb8 Raxb8 11. e3 Bxf1 12. Kxf1 Qb5+ 13. Qe2 Qb3 14. h4 {
Avrukh,B (2603)-Pelletier,Y (2587) Mulhouse 2011 (1/2-1/2, 27)} Rfc8 $1 {
Why precisely this rook? The answer is given by Black's plan:} 15. Ne1 b5 16.
Rh3 a5 17. h5 b4 18. axb4 a4 $44 {The weakness on b2 offers Black enough
compensation.}) 9. g3 ({The only way to deviate from the usual lines where
a2-a3 would not be very useful.} 9. e3 {transposes to one of the lines below,
where a2-a3 is not common.} c5 10. Bd3 c4 11. Bc2 Nc6 12. h4 {The only way to
take advantage of the fact that White has not castled yet.} b5 13. Ng5 h6 14.
Qh5 Qe8 15. Nf3 f5 {We will have this structure in some later lines.} 16. g4
Qxh5 17. gxh5 Bf6 18. Rg1 Kh8 19. Kd2 Be6 20. Be5 {Eljanov,P (2693)
-Kasimdzhanov,R (2695) Nalchik 2009 (1/2-1/2, 65)} Bxe5 21. Nxe5 Nxe5 22. dxe5
f4 $132) 9... c5 10. Bg2 Be6 11. O-O Nc6 {Black develops the same way as in
Line 6.} 12. Qa4 Qd7 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. Ng5 {Fressinet,L (2653)
-Alekseev,E (2715) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009 (1/2-1/2, 51)} Bxg5 16. Bxg5 Nd4 17.
Rxd4 (17. Qxd7 Rxd7 18. e4 Bg4 $15) 17... cxd4 18. Qxd4 Rdc8 {White has some
compensation for the exchange, but in view of the threat ...Rc2 Black's
chances are a bit better.}) ({The rare} 6. Qc2 {has the same ideas and
drawbacks as 7.Qc2 below.} b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. g3 (8. e3 {transposes to 7. Qc2
below}) 8... c5 9. Rd1 Nc6 10. Bg2 Be6 11. O-O Rc8 12. dxc5 (12. Qb1 h6 13. h3
Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. e3 {1/2-1/2 Maninang,R (2350)-Rodriguez Vargas, O (2485)
Surakarta 1982} c4 16. b3 Na5 17. b4 Nc6 18. a3 a5 19. b5 Ne7 $15) 12... bxc5
13. Ng5 Qe8 $5 {Preparing to activate the queen along the h5-e8 diagonal after
the exchange on e6, while also avoiding problems along the d-file.} 14. Qa4 (
14. Nxe6 fxe6 {offers Black kingside counterplay.} 15. Bh3 Nd4 16. Qd3 Qh5 17.
Kg2 g5 18. e3 g4 19. Bxg4 Nxg4 20. h3 Nxf2 21. Rxf2 Nc6 $15) (14. h4 Nd4 15.
Qd2 Bg4 $11) 14... Bd7 15. Nxd5 Nd4 16. Nxe7+ (16. Qxa7 Nxe2+ 17. Kh1 Nxd5 18.
Bxd5 Bc6 $15) 16... Qxe7 17. Qxa7 h6 18. Nf3 Nxe2+ 19. Kh1 Nxf4 20. gxf4 Ra8
21. Qc7 Rfc8 {White should agree to a move repetition by keeping his queen on
the queenside as if} 22. Qe5 Qf8 23. a3 $6 Bb5 24. Rfe1 $6 Ng4 $19) 6... b6 $5
{This is far from the most popular move, but not really a rarity either. After
comparing to the main lines,} (6... c5 {and}) (6... Nbd7 {, where play usually
flows along extensively analyzed lines and Black is close to equality but
still struggling a bit, I have come to the conclusion that we do not need to
deviate from our usual Tartakower setup. This system not only has a strong
resemblance with the main Tartakower lines but is also flexible enough to
avoid falling into the opponent's deep preparation. For this purpose, I have
built up a repertoire offering Black a choice between three main structures
against most of White's answers. Since 5.Bf4 is so popular nowadays, it makes
sense to alternate those structures during a tournament.}) 7. cxd5 {Before
anything else, we should know how to answer the early central exchange.} (7.
Be2 Bb7 {does not have independent value:} 8. O-O (8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {
transposes to line 4.}) 8... c5 9. Rc1 Nbd7 10. h3 $5 (10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5
exd5 {transposes to Line 8.}) 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 cxd4 12. exd4 (12. Qxd4 Rc8
13. Rfd1 {Seemingly the most consistent. Against other moves Black could play .
.. a7-a6 followed by ...b6-b5.} Bxf3 14. gxf3 e5 15. Bxe5 Rxc4 16. Qxc4 Nxe5
17. Rxd8 Nxc4 18. Rxf8+ Bxf8 {The ending remains interesting, but material and
chances are about equal.}) 12... Rc8 13. Bb3 (13. Bd3 Nd5) 13... Ne4 $11) (7.
Qc2 {increases the latent pressure on c7, but is an early queen commitment.}
Bb7 8. cxd5 ({White does not get much out of refraining from this exchange, as
his queen will be unsafe if the c-file opens.} 8. Rd1 c5 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O
cxd4 11. exd4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Rc8 13. Bb3 Nd5 14. Bg3 Bb4 $15) 8... exd5 9. Be2 (
9. Bd3 {exposes the bishop to} c5 10. O-O Nc6 11. a3 c4 {, when there is no
retreat along the b1-h7 diagonal available.} 12. Bf5 g6 13. Bh3 a6 $11) 9... c5
10. dxc5 bxc5 11. O-O Nh5 $5 12. Be5 Nd7 13. Rfd1 {Ravi,L (2419) -Prathamesh,S
(2366) Mumbai 2003 (1-0, 62)} Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Nf6 $11) 7... exd5 {In this line
we will examine a few essential aspects of this genuine Tartakower structure.
The lines below may arise from different move orders, too, if Black meets a
later cxd5 with ...exd5. The lines with ... exd5 are traditionally considered
to put Black under pressure, but I have discovered that things are not
one-sided and, at least as a reserve variation, it should work out well.} ({
The main line is} 7... Nxd5 {and will be examined in the next lines.}) 8. Bd3 {
The most active continuation.} ({The seemingly modest} 8. Be2 {is also
interesting. Instead of putting the bid on a kingside attack, White prepares
to put pressure on the hanging pawns with Ne5 and Bf3.} Bb7 9. O-O c5 10. Ne5
Nbd7 11. Bf3 (11. dxc5 Nxc5 ({Now is a good moment to switch to the Isolani
structure. Not only are the pawns hanging a bit more than usual after} 11...
bxc5 12. Bf3 Nb6 13. a4 a5 14. Nb5 {, but as we will see in the mainline the
bishop is not optimally placed on f4 in the isolani structure.}) 12. Nf3 Ne6 (
12... Nfe4 13. Be5 {Farago,I (2475)-Southam, T (2335) Luxembourg 1990 (1/2-1/2,
48)} f6 14. Bd4 Rc8 15. Rc1 Ne6 $11 {The bishop deprives the knight of its
natural square and is also vulnerable.}) 13. Be5 a6 $5 {The start of a typical
queenside expansion.} 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Rc2 b5 16. Rd2 (16. Nd4 Nd7 {forces the
bishop to retreat far away from the d4-square.}) 16... Qe8 (16... Qb6 $5) 17.
Qb1 Ne4 $132) 11... Nxe5 {The best way to release the central tension.} (11...
Ne4 $6 {Belousov,G (2222)-Duda,A (2055) Pardubice 2014 (1-0, 35)} 12. Bxe4 dxe4
13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. dxc5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxc5 16. Bd6 $14) 12. Bxe5 (12. dxe5 Ne4
$11) 12... Ne4 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Rc1 {Skema, L-Max,H Munich 1936 (1-0, 52)} Qe7
15. Bd4 Rad8 $11 {Black has a very compact development and central activity.
In the long run, he can consider starting a kingside attack with ...f7-f5,
while for White it is not easy to formulate a concrete plan.}) 8... Bb7 9. O-O
c5 10. Ne5 Nc6 {This is not the most typical square for the knight in this
structure, but as we will see Black needs to leave the h3-c8 diagonal
available for the queen.} (10... Nbd7 11. Qf3 $14 {offers White good attacking
chances.}) 11. Qf3 (11. Rc1 {does not change anything essentially after} Qc8)
11... Qc8 $1 {The queen is heading for e6. We know already that this is one of
Black's best regroupings.} 12. Rac1 (12. Rad1 {was played in a few games but
Black should have stuck to his plan with} Qe6 $1 $146) 12... Qe6 13. Nxc6 (13.
Nb5 {Hoang,T (2350)-Mikhalevski,A (2470) Budapest 1997 (1/2-1/2, 44)} Rfc8 14.
Bg3 Ne4 $11) (13. Rfd1 a6 {Controlling b5 and also threatening ...c5-c4
followed by ...b7-b5.} 14. a3 $5 Rad8 {Black is well regrouped and defends his
hanging pawns quite well.}) 13... Bxc6 14. Rfd1 c4 $1 $146 (14... Ne4 {offers
White some chances to retain an edge.} 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qg3 Rfd8 (16... cxd4
$1) 17. Bc7 Rd7 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Rxd7 Qxd7 20. Rd1 Qf5 21. h3 h5 {Kantsler,B 
(2495)-Mikhalevski,A (2470) Beersheba 1997 (1-0, 105) The position may be
close to equality, but optically White's position is more pleasant due to his
control of the weakened central squares.}) 15. Bb1 b5 $11 {With promising
queenside counterplay. This system is useful to keep in mind as it allows
Black to meet a wide range of white move orders, including the exchange
variation, without the need of memorizing long forced lines.} *

