1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Nxd5 {Like in similar lines with the bishop on h4 (the genuine Tartakower
lines), this is the most principled continuation. True, the reasons are a bit
different here.} (8. Bg3 {wastes a tempo, offering Black easy development.} Bb7
9. Bd3 c5 10. O-O Nxc3 (10... cxd4 11. exd4 Nc6 $11 {is also good, as the
bishop does not stand too well on g3 with a white isolani, either.}) 11. bxc3
Nd7 12. e4 Nf6 13. Qe2 Nh5 14. Be5 cxd4 15. cxd4 Rc8 (15... f6 $5 16. Bg3 Nxg3
17. hxg3 Rc8 $11) 16. Rfd1 (16. h3 f6 17. Bh2 Bd6 18. Qe3 Bxh2+ 19. Kxh2 Qd6+
20. g3 $13 {Dautov}) (16. Ne1 g6 17. Nc2 f6 18. Bg3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Rc3 $15 {
Dautov}) (16. Nd2 g6 17. g4 f6 18. gxh5 fxe5 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. dxe5 Bc5 $44 {
Dautov}) 16... f6 17. Bg3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Qc7 19. a4 Rfd8 $1 (19... Kh8 $6 {
unnecessarily offered White a tempo in Sasikiran,K (2668)-Vaganian,R (2640)
Mallorca 2004 (1/2-1/2, 60)}) 20. a5 (20. Ba6 Bb4 $1 21. Rab1 Bxa6 22. Qxa6 Ba5
23. d5 exd5 24. exd5 Qc4 $1 $15) 20... bxa5 21. Qa2 Rd6 22. Qxa5 Qxa5 23. Rxa5
a6 $11 {Dautov.}) 8... Qxd5 {The most active continuation, implying a pawn
sacrifice. This is the second typical structure in which Black occupies d5
with a piece.} (8... exd5 {would most likely transpose to Line 6, being the
third typical structure, with black hanging pawns and missing knights from f6
and c3.}) 9. Bxc7 {It is just natural to first of all check what happens if
White takes the pawn. In the next lines we will examine} (9. Bd3) (9. Be2) ({
and} 9. a3) 9... Bb4+ {An essential check, forcing White to move into a pin
and leave g2 hanging from the perspective of his kingside development.} 10. Nd2
Nc6 $1 {The knight anticipates White's practically only reasonable answer by
stepping closer to the queenside light squares. Besides, the hanging bishop on
c7 will later cause White more loss of time.} (10... Ba6 {allows} 11. Bxb8 $1 {
, reducing Black's attacking potential a bit.} (11. f3 Bxf1 12. Rxf1 Nc6 13. a3
Rac8 14. Bg3 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Na5 16. Rd1 {Jorczik,J (2405)-Baramidze,D (2613)
Germany 2014 (0-1, 68)} Nb3 17. Qe2 Nc1 $11) 11... Bxf1 12. Kxf1 Raxb8 13. Nf3
Rbc8 14. Qd3 Rc7 15. a3 Be7 16. e4 {Black may have some compensation for the
pawn, but finding a clear plan is not easy, as the knight ensures White some
stability.}) (10... Bb7 {looks natural, but we will see that the bishop will
be useful on a different diagonal.}) 11. a3 ({The developing plan based on} 11.
f3 {is slow and likely to offer Black tactical possibilities.} Bd7 12. Be2 {
is relatively better, but it does not change Black's intentions.} (12. Kf2 Nxd4
13. exd4 Qxd4+ 14. Ke1 Rac8 15. Bg3 (15. Rc1 Ba4 $1 16. b3 Qe3+ 17. Be2 Bb5 18.
Kf1 Rfd8 $1 $19) 15... Ba4 16. b3 Bxd2+ 17. Qxd2 Qxa1+) 12... Rac8 13. Bg3 Nxd4
14. exd4 Qxd4 {, with a very strong initiative against the uncastled king.})
11... Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Na5 13. Rd1 Bd7 {Preparing the queenside invasion with ...
Ba4 and ...Nb3.} 14. b4 {What else? Oner,O (1960)-Zor,A (2150) Antalya 2018 
(0-1, 75)} Rac8 15. bxa5 Rxc7 16. f3 (16. axb6 axb6 17. f3 Ra8 $11) 16... Rfc8
17. Bd3 Bb5 18. axb6 axb6 19. O-O Bxd3 20. Qxd3 Rc3 $11 *

