1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Bd3 {A developing move, keeping Bxc7 in reserve.} Qa5+ {Black's
queen was exposed on d5 so he uses the first possibility to use it for keeping
the enemy king uncastled.} 10. Kf1 {White plans a long regrouping finishing
with Kh2. But this offers Black time to organize his counterplay.} (10. Nd2 Ba6
$1 {Black continues developing while also delaying White's castle.} 11. Bxa6 (
11. Qe2 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 c5 {After removing the threat Be4 and clearing some
space for his queen, Black can finally break in the centre.} 13. O-O cxd4 14.
Nb3 Qa6 $11) 11... Qxa6 12. Qe2 Rc8 $5 $146 ({I find it useful to prepare ...
c7-c5 as} 12... c5 {offers White some light endgame initiative:} 13. dxc5 Bxc5
14. Bxb8 Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2 Raxb8 16. Rac1 Rfc8 17. Rc2 Bd6 18. Rhc1 Rxc2 19. Rxc2
{White's position is more active but Black will gradually equalize with
planful play:} Kf8 20. Rc6 Ke7 21. Nc4 Rd8 22. f4 Bb8 23. b4 g5 24. g3 gxf4 25.
gxf4 Rg8 26. Kf2 Kd7 27. b5 Rg6 28. Nd2 e5 29. Rc4 {1/2-1/2 Yakovich,Y (2480)
-Gelfand,B Minsk 1986}) 13. a3 (13. Qxa6 Nxa6 14. Ke2 c5 {, and Black is
prepared to re-capture on c5 with the knight.}) (13. Rc1 Qxa2) (13. Ne4 Qa5+
14. Nc3 c5 $11) 13... c5 14. dxc5 Rxc5 {This is an important difference with
respect to the game quoted above. Black controls the c-file already.} 15. Bxb8
Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Rxb8 17. Rac1 Rbc8 {, with at least equal play.}) (10. Ke2 {
plans to develop the king's rook and only then retreat with the king, if still
necessary.} Ba6 11. a3 (11. Bxc7 {wastes too much time and opens the c-file
for Black's rooks.} Bxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Na6 13. Bg3 Nb4 14. Qb3 Qa6+ 15. Kd2 Rfc8
$40 {with a dangerous attack.}) 11... c5 12. b4 $5 (12. dxc5 bxc5 $15 {leaves
White vulnerable along the d-file (and possibly along the b-file).} 13. Qc2 Rd8
14. Rhd1 Rxd3 15. Rxd3 Nc6 16. Rad1 Rd8 $17) 12... Bxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Qa4 14. bxc5
(14. Rhc1 Nd7 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Bd6 Bxd6 17. Qxd6 Rac8 18. bxc5 Qb5+ 19. Qd3
Qxd3+ 20. Kxd3 Nxc5+ $11 {Esen,B (2301)-Boensch,U (2547)/Saint Vincent 2005})
14... bxc5 15. Rhc1 Nd7 $11 {Radjabov,T (2744)-Carlsen,M (2815) Medias 2011 (1/
2-1/2, 29)}) 10... Ba6 ({A necessary move, ensuring the queen with some
freedom and avoiding} 10... c5 $2 11. Be4) 11. Bxc7 {White has to take the
pawn as otherwise, he would have no compensation for the time wasted on
completing his development.} (11. h4 c5 12. Bxb8 Raxb8 ({With hindsight,} 12...
Rfxb8 {may be even better:} 13. Bxa6 Qxa6+ 14. Qe2 Qb7 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. b3 a5
{and the rook is useful on a8.}) 13. Bxa6 Qxa6+ 14. Qe2 Qb7 15. dxc5 bxc5 16.
b3 a5 $15 {Lima,D (2535)-Jatoba de Oliveira Reis,P (2377) Natal 2019 (В1/2-В1/
2, 44)}) 11... Bxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Na6 13. Bg3 Nb4 {It can be easily seen that
Black has gained a few tempi for his initiative.} 14. Qe2 {The safest retreat.}
(14. Qb3 Rfc8 15. h3 Rc2 16. Ne1 $5 (16. Kg1 Qd5 $1 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. a3 Nd3
$11) 16... Rd2 $1 (16... Rc6 {is a bit slow} 17. Kg1 {Graf,A (2613)-Boensch,U 
(2547) Germany 2005 (1/2-1/2, 40)}) 17. Kg1 (17. Qc3 Qb5+ 18. Kg1 Qe2 $11) (17.
a3 Rc8 18. Kg1 Qd5 19. Qxd5 Nxd5 20. Rb1 h5 $44) 17... Rc8 18. Kh2 h5 19. h4
Qd5 $44) 14... Rac8 $1 ({For reasons far from clear at this point,} 14... Rfc8
{is less accurate:} 15. a3 Qa4 16. Kg1 Na2 ({The same line as recommended
below does not work out so well here:} 16... Nd5 17. Ne1 Bb4 18. Nd3 Rc2 19.
Qg4 Nf6 20. Qf3 $1 {Gaining an essential tempo by attacking the rook on a8.
This is the difference!} Rac8 21. h3) 17. h3 Nc1 18. Qf1 Qc2 19. Kh2 Ne2 20.
Be5 Qxb2 21. d5 $36 {Caruana,F (2832)-Nakamura,H (2746) London 2018 (0-1, 54)})
15. a3 {The same plan as in Caruana's game.} (15. Ne1 Rc6 16. a3 Rfc8 17. Rd1
Na2 18. Qd2 Qa4 19. f4 Rc1 $17 {with a massive invasion in Shishkin,V (2513)
-Thesing,M (2425) Baia Sprie 2010 (0-1, 32)}) 15... Qa4 16. Kg1 Nd5 $1 17. Ne1
Bb4 18. Nd3 Rc2 19. Qg4 Nf6 (19... f5 {is also good. With the rook on a8 it
would look less natural, of course.} 20. Qf3 Bd2 21. h3 Qb3 {, and Black will
most likely retrieve the pawn due to his strong queenside pressure.}) 20. Qf3
Bd2 21. h3 Qa6 $132 {White has serious stability problems.} *

