1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Be2 {Even though this looks more modest than 9.Bd3, it offers
White some additional possibilities.} Bb7 {Since the enemy bishop is generally
less active than in the previous line, Black can develop slowly. With the
bishop on d3, the last move would run into 10.Qc2 with a double attack and if
10...h6 then 11.Qxc7, gaining more time.} ({One important point is that if} 
9... Ba6 {Basso,P (2417)-Brunello,S (2557) Rome 2016 (0-1, 50)} 10. Bxc7 Qa5+
11. Kf1 Rc8 12. Bg3 {the bishop exchange would take place on e2, thus yielding
White an extra tempo with respect to the previous lines based on ...Na6-b4.}) (
{Another point is that} 9... c5 $2 {runs into} 10. Ne5 $18 {followed by Bf3.})
({Or if} 9... Bd6 10. Nd2 Bxf4 11. Bf3 Qb5 12. Bxa8 Bd6 13. Bf3 e5 14. Be2 Qxb2
15. O-O $16 {Swiercz,D (2663)-Bruzon Batista,L (2646) Philadelphia 2018 (1-0,
76)}) 10. Bxc7 {The critical continuation.} ({If} 10. O-O Bd6 $5 (10... c5 11.
dxc5 Bxc5 12. Qc2 {leaves the black queen exposed.}) 11. Bxd6 (11. Bg3 Bxg3 12.
hxg3 Nd7 13. Qa4 a5 14. Rfd1 Rac8 15. Rac1 Nf6 16. Ne1 e5 $11) 11... cxd6 {
Black's queen's activity and his lack of weaknesses compensate for White's
slightly superiority in space.} 12. Bd3 Nd7 (12... Ba6 {is also a safe way to
reach comfortable equality.} 13. Rc1 Qb7 14. e4 Nd7 15. Qe2 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Rac8
$11) 13. e4 Qh5 14. Qd2 Nf6 (14... Rac8 $5 {may be more to the point, leaving
the question open about how Black will attack the enemy centre, with .. .e6-e5,
...d6-d5 or ...f7-f5.}) 15. Rfe1 Rac8 16. a4 a5 17. Ra3 Bc6 18. Bb1 b5 19. axb5
Qxb5 20. e5 dxe5 21. Nxe5 (21. dxe5 Rfd8 22. Rd3 Nd5 {is stable for Black.})
21... Qb4 22. Qxb4 axb4 23. Ra7 Bd5 $11 {Parligras,M (2645)-Bhakti,K (2312)
Abu Dhabi 2018 (1/2-1/2, 49)}) 10... Qa5+ {A familiar reaction to the pawn
grabbing.} 11. Kf1 Nd7 12. h4 {Clearing the h2-square for the king and
ensuring some stability for the bishop.} ({If} 12. h3 Rac8 13. Bg3 (13. Bf4 {
runs into} g5) 13... Nf6 14. Kg1 Ne4 15. Bf4 Rfd8 16. a3 f6 {, preparing ...
e6-e5. White does not have a clear way to complete his regrouping as f2 is
hanging.}) 12... Rac8 13. Bf4 Rfd8 {Completing the regrouping before embarking
on concrete operations.} (13... Bxf3 {is premature because after} 14. gxf3 e5
15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Kg2 {the king reaches g2 without loss of time.}) 14. Kg1 ({If
} 14. a3 {Black has to change his plans:} Ba6 $1 ({A logical reaction to
White's weakening his light squares on the previous move.} 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3
e5 {does not work out so well because of} 16. b4 Qd5 17. dxe5 Qe6 18. Kg2 Nxe5
19. Qa4 Rd2 20. Qb5 $1 $14) 15. Kg1 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Qa4 {with promising
queenside pressure.}) 14... Bxf3 $1 15. Bxf3 ({If} 15. gxf3 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5
17. Qe1 {Black has several ways to use his superior mobilization. One of them
is} Qd5 18. Kg2 Nd3 19. Bxd3 Qxd3 20. Rc1 Bf6 21. b3 Rc2 $11 {, retrieving the
pawn soon.}) 15... e5 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. hxg5 exd4 18. Qxd4 Qxg5 19. Rh5 Qf6 $11
{Ding,L (2769)-So,W (2799) Berlin 2018 (1/2-1/2, 31) Black's superior
coordination compensates for the theoretical bishop's superiority over the
knight in the endgame.} *

