1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Nxd5 Qxd5 9. a3 {Since checks along the e1-a5 diagonal were Black's main
source of counterplay, White's last move makes sense. But it wastes an
important developing tempo.} c5 {This seems to work out best under the given
circumstances, as White is a tempo behind in development with respect to the
previous lines.} (9... Ba6 {In connection with the next move, this is a
familiar method to delay White's castle. But it seems that White is well
prepared to take the pawn now:} 10. Bxa6 Qa5+ 11. Nd2 $5 (11. Ke2 {This
ambitious move, heading for an ending (or queenless middlegame) in which the
king's presence in the centre could be useful. is not the most critical.} Qxa6+
12. Qd3 Qb7 13. b4 Nd7 14. Rhc1 {Suba,M (2464)-Danner,G (2422) Arco 2010 (1-0,
65)} Rfc8 15. Rab1 (15. Rc2 c5 16. Rac1 a5 17. b5 a4 18. Kf1 h6 $11) 15... a5
16. b5 c5 17. Kf1 (17. a4 cxd4 {[%csl Gg2]} 18. exd4 Nf6) 17... a4) 11... Qxa6
12. Bxc7 $5 $146 (12. Qe2 {is too soft.} Qb7 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rfd1 c5 15. Qf3
Qxf3 16. Nxf3 Rfc8 17. Rac1 Kf8 18. Kf1 cxd4 19. exd4 Nf6 $15 {Grujic,Z (2362)
-Iordachescu,V (2584) Zlatibor 2007 (0-1, 45)}) 12... Nd7 (12... Qb7 13. Rc1
Qxg2 14. Qf3 Qxf3 15. Nxf3 $14 {followed by Ke2 leaves White with a strong
centre and better development.}) 13. Bg3 e5 14. Qe2 {White cannot allow the
centre to open, nor the enemy knight to get to c5-d3.} Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2 exd4 16.
exd4 {Black has some initiative for the lost pawn, but he will have to
struggle for a while on his way to equality, if this even exists.} Rfe8 17.
Rhe1 (17. Kf3 Bf6 18. Nc4 Bxd4 19. Rad1 Ne5+ 20. Bxe5 Bxe5 21. Rd7 Re6 $11)
17... Bf6+ (17... Bxa3+ 18. Kd3 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 $14 Bxb2 $2 20. Nc4) 18. Kd3 Red8
19. Nf3 Nc5+ 20. Ke3 Ne6 21. Be5 $14) 10. dxc5 (10. Be2 cxd4 $5 (10... Ba6 $5
$11) (10... Bb7 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. O-O Rd8 13. Qb1 Nc6 14. Rc1 Qf5 15. Qxf5 exf5
16. Rc2 {1-0 (50) Ivanchuk,V (2726)-Fridman,D (2649) Berlin 2015}) 11. Nxd4 Bb7
$11 12. Bf3 Qa5+ 13. b4 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 (14. Qxf3 Bxb4+ $1) 14... Qa6) 10... Qxc5
11. Rc1 (11. Be2 Ba6 12. O-O Rd8 13. Qe1 {Zhou,W (2560)-Wu,W (2442) Jiangsu
Wuxi 2008 (1/2-1/2, 21)} Qc2 $5 $11) 11... Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Na6 {
White does not have enough resources to sustain his initiative in this almost
symmetrical structure.} 14. b4 ({More critical than} 14. Nc4 Rd8 15. Be2 Bb7
16. O-O f6 {Restricting White's knight and dark-squared bishop.} ({But a
simpler way to take advantage of the missing b2-b4 was} 16... g5 {, forcing
the bishop to occupy an exposed square in view of the knight's centralization.}
17. Bg3 Nc5 18. b4 Ne4 $11) 17. b4 Kf7 18. Rfd1 {Matviishen,V (2350)-Sabuk,P 
(2407) Lvov 2015 (1/2-1/2, 56)} (18. f3 Rac8 19. Rcd1 e5 20. Bg3 Nc7 21. f4
exf4 22. exf4 Ne6 $11 {Tomczak,M (2391)-Sabuk,P (2368) Gorzow Wielkopolski
2017 (1/2-1/2, 35)}) 18... Rac8 19. f3 Nb8 $11) (14. Rxc8 $2 Raxc8 15. Bxa6
Rc1+) 14... Bb7 15. Bd3 $5 (15. f3 {This solid but slow move offers Black a
tempo for his development. But there does not seem to be anything better.} Rac8
16. Rc4 Bd5 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 $11 {followed by ...Nb8 or ...Nc7 soon.}) (15. e4 {
is even slightly risky as it exposes White too much.} Rac8 16. Kd1 Rxc1+ 17.
Kxc1 Nb8 18. Kb2 Rd8 19. Be2 g5 20. Be3 f5 $15 {Jakubowski,K (2529)
-Krysztofiak,M (2378) Poronin 2016 (1/2-1/2, 39)}) 15... Bxg2 16. Rg1 Bb7 17.
Bh6 Bf6 {White's attack is not dangerous as his development is incomplete yet.}
18. Ke2 {The best idea is to complete mobilization, of course.} (18. Ne4 Bxe4
19. Bxe4 Rac8 $17) (18. Bxa6 Bxa6 19. Ne4 Bb2 20. Rb1 Rfc8 21. Rg3 Be5 22. f4
Bd3 $17) (18. Be4 Rfc8 $17) 18... Kh8 19. Bf4 Rad8 20. Nc4 Nb8 $11 {Even
though White has some pressure for the pawn, in the absence of queens Black
should not have any concrete problems.} *

