1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 {White
continues developing, keeping the idea of cxd5 in reserve.} c5 {Black is
heading for the hanging pawns structure (according to our previous
classification it could be structure number one or three).} (7... Bb7 {
restricts Black's possibilities.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Better is} 8... exd5 {,
transposing to structure number one.}) 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 (9... exd5 {runs into} 10.
Qc2 $16 {with a double attack.}) 10. Bxc7 {With Bd3 on the board, Black's
compensation is not very clear.}) (7... dxc4 {is a logical way of exploiting
the early bishop's development. In principle, Black should be able to
gradually equalize with accurate play, but this is not my main idea when
recommending 6.. .b6. Here is a top-level example.} 8. Bxc4 Bb7 9. O-O c5 10.
dxc5 (10. Qe2 cxd4 11. Rfd1 Nc6 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Qc8 $11) 10... Qxd1 ({
One of Black's main problems in this symmetrical structure is to find a safe
square for the queen. Therefore, exchanging it is a reasonable decision, even
though it offers White a developing tempo. If} 10... Bxc5 11. Qe2 Nbd7 12. Rfd1
Qe7 13. a3 a5 {as played in a few games, Black is a bit on the edge.}) 11.
Rfxd1 Bxc5 12. Nb5 Nbd7 13. Nd6 Bd5 14. Bb5 Nh5 $5 {Black will equalize with a
few small tricks.} 15. Bxd7 Nxf4 16. Nb5 Rad8 17. exf4 Rxd7 18. Ne5 Rb7 19. Nc3
f6 20. Nd3 Bc6 21. Nxc5 bxc5 22. Rd6 Rc8 23. b3 Kf7 24. Re1 Bd7 25. Ne4 Ke7 26.
Ra6 Rcc7 $11 {Gelfand,B (2738)-Carlsen,M (2837) Astana 2012 (1/2-1/2, 45)}) 8.
cxd5 Nxd5 {Heading for structure three, which will be examined in this and the
next line in some detail.} (8... exd5 {would lead to structure number one.}) 9.
Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 {With ...c5-c4 in the air, this exchange makes sense.} (10.
Ne5 {This attacking move is less problematic than in the positions with
knights on f6 and c3, as the central knight is not entirely stable.} Bb7 (10...
cxd4 11. exd4 Bb4+ {gives up the tension too easily, just for the sake of this
check.} 12. Kf1 Qf6 13. Qh5 h6 14. g3 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Kg2 $14 {Jones,G 
(2593) -Illner,A (2345) Caleta 2011 (1-0, 22)}) (10... Bf6 {leads to animated
play, where Black's position may be less dangerous than it looks:} 11. Qh5 g6
12. Qf3 Bxe5 13. Bxe5 Nc6 14. Bf6 Qd6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. O-O c4 17. Bc2 Bg4 $1
18. Qf4 Qxf4 {1/2-1/2 Gelfand,B (2758)-Jakovenko,D (2736) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009}
) ({But} 10... c4 $2 {is precisely what White had prepared against with his
previous move.} 11. Nxc4 dxc4 12. Be4 g5 13. Bg3 f5 14. Bxa8 f4 15. Be4 $16)
11. O-O {Ibragimov,I (2550)-Radulov,I (2400) Heraklio 1993 (1-0, 41)} (11. Qf3
Nc6 12. O-O Nxe5 13. Bxe5 g6 14. Rfd1 Qd7 $11) 11... c4 $146 12. Bf5 Nc6 13.
Qh5 g6 14. Nxg6 {Otherwise Black may take over the initiative by advancing his
queenside pawns.} fxg6 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Qxg6+ Kh8 $11) (10. Qc2 {offers Black
a choice.} h6 ({Even though the position may remain equal after this move, I
am not enthusiastic about weakening g6.} 10... f5 $5 11. h4 c4 12. Be2 Nc6 $11)
(10... g6 $5 {may be the most solid as White is not in time to create
dangerous kingside threats:} 11. h4 Nc6 12. a3 c4 13. h5 Bd7 14. Be2 g5 $15)
11. Ne5 cxd4 12. exd4 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 f6 15. Nf3 {The knight has
to defend d4, but it might soon have the possibility to go to g6.} Re8+ 16. Kf1
Ba6 17. g3 Re4 (17... Bxd3+ $5 18. Qxd3 Qd7 19. Kg2 Nc6 20. h4 Ne7 21. h5 Nf5 {
and Black is only symbolically worse.}) 18. Kg2 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Nc6 20. Rac1 {
Onischuk,A (2666)-Morrison,W (2330) Rockville 2012 (1-0, 29)} Qd7 21. Rc3 Rc8
22. Rhc1 Ne7 $11 {and again Black seems to be doing fine.}) (10. O-O {is
examined in the next line.}) 10... bxc5 11. O-O Nc6 {The fastest way to
develop and create the potential possibility of ...d5-d4 or even ...c5-c4
without giving up control over d4.} 12. Rc1 Be6 {As we know from the
Tartakower lines, this is the best square for the bishop if the exchange in
the centre takes place early.} 13. a3 {Preparing Qc2.} (13. b3 {slows down ...
c5-c4 but offers Black a clear target.} a5 (13... Nb4 $5 14. Bb1 a5 {may be
more accurate.}) 14. Qe2 (14. Nd4 $5 {is interesting, but Black seems to hold
his own:} Nxd4 15. exd4 cxd4 16. Bc7 Qd7 17. Be5 Rfc8 18. Bxd4 Bf5) 14... h6
15. Rfd1 Qb6 16. Bb1 a4 17. bxa4 (17. Qc2 f5) 17... Qa5 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. exd4
c4 20. Qc2 f5 21. Re1 (21. Qe2 Ra6) 21... Ra6 22. Re3 Bf6 23. Qe2 Bd7 $15 {
Chistiakova,T (2310)-Nechaeva,M (2261) Nojabrsk 2005 (0-1, 37)}) (13. Ne5 {
considerably simplifies Black's coordination.} Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Rc8 15. Qe2 (15.
Ba6 Rc6 16. Qa4 Qb6 17. Bb5 Rcc8 $11) 15... Bf6 $11) (13. h3 h6 14. Bb1 Rc8 (
14... f5 15. Nd4 $1 {Holzke,F (2506)-Levin,F (2482) Germany 2012 (1/2-1/2, 30)}
) 15. Qc2 f5 $11 {The weakening implied by this move is compensated by the 
(now) passive bishop on b1 and Black's excellent control in the centre.}) (13.
Qa4 {Malakhatko,V (2543)-Galinsky,T (2430) Kiev 2004 (1/2-1/2, 39)} Qb6 14. Ng5
Bxg5 15. Bxg5 Ne5 16. Bb1 c4 $11) 13... Qb6 14. Qc2 h6 15. e4 {Iturrizaga
Bonelli,E (2624)-Batsiashvili,N (2466) Benasque 2016 (1/2-1/2, 100) This was
the plan White had been playing for (with the actual regrouping it is hard to
figure out anything else) but Black is well prepared against it.} Rac8 $5 $146
{A useful developing move, inviting White to show his cards.} 16. exd5 (16.
Rfd1 $2 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bb3) (16. e5 $6 c4 (16... g5 $5 17. Bg3 g4 18. Nh4 Nd4
19. Qb1 c4 $17 {with overwhelming initiative.}) 17. Bh7+ (17. Be2 g5 18. Bg3 g4
19. Nh4 Nd4 20. Qd1 Bg5 $17) 17... Kh8 18. Bf5 Bc5 $17) 16... Bxd5 17. Bh7+ Kh8
18. Be4 (18. Bf5 Bxf3 $17 19. Bxc8 Nd4 20. Qd2 Qg6 21. Bh3 Bxg2 $1) 18... Bxe4
19. Qxe4 Qxb2 {White must still prove his compensation for the pawn.} *

