1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Rc1 {A flexible
move, inhibiting an early ...dxc4, as White has not moved his bishop yet.} Bb7
{Black chooses another gambit line.} ({Alternatively he can also opt for one
of the hanging pawns structures with} 7... c5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 (8... exd5) 9. Nxd5
exd5 {In both cases Rc1 is not especially useful at this point.}) 8. cxd5 ({If
} 8. Be2 {, Black can go for the hanging pawns after having avoided Bd3:} c5 9.
O-O Nbd7 (9... Nc6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14.
Bxe5 Qb6 15. Bf3 Rfd8 $11) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. b4 $5
(13. Qa4 Nf6 14. Ba6 Bxa6 15. Qxa6 Qb6 16. Qe2 Ne4 17. Rfd1 Bf6 18. Be5 Rfd8
19. Rc2 Rac8 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 {Spassov, L (2428)-Fernandez Borrego,P (2229)
Ourense 2008 (1/2-1/2, 54)}) (13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Qb6 15. Bd3 Qe6 16. Bg3
Rac8 17. Re1 Bf6 $11 {Sapunov,E-Burmakin, V (2560) St Petersburg 1998 (1/2-1/2,
62)}) 13... c4 $1 (13... cxb4 14. Bc7 Qe8 15. Bb5 $16) 14. Nd4 (14. Ne5 Nxe5
15. Bxe5 Bxb4 16. Rb1 Qe7 17. Qd4 f6 $15 {White does not have full
compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Bf6 15. Qa4 Ne5 16. Rfd1 Qb6 17. Rb1 Rac8
18. b5 Rfe8 (18... c3 $6 {prematurely exposes the pawn and concedes control
over d3 and b3.} 19. Rbc1 Nc4 20. Qb4 Nb2 21. Re1 a5 22. Qd6 $14 {Sturua,Z 
(2585)-Ovsejevitsch,S (2465) Berlin 1997 (1-0, 52)}) 19. Qb4 {Planning a4-a5.}
a5 20. Qc3 Ng6 21. Bg3 Nf8 22. Qc2 Ne6 $11) ({If} 8. Bd3 {Black can play
trickier than above, transposing to the hanging pawns as the bishop is exposed
on d3.} c5 9. cxd5 (9. O-O Nc6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. dxc5 Rfd8 $1 {
Black does not have this extra tempo after Be2.} 13. Bb1 Qxd1 14. Rcxd1 Rxd1
15. Rxd1 Bxc5 $11) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd5 11. O-O Nxf4 12. exf4 Bf6 (12... Nc6
$5) (12... Na6 $5) 13. Nf3 Nc6 $11 {Bourdageau,L (1635) -Steimbach,I (1947)
Karlsruhe 2018 (0-1, 43)}) 8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. a3 {A familiar move,
preparing to defend the dangerous diagonal.} (10. Rxc7 {is risky:} Bb4+ 11. Nd2
Na6 12. Rxb7 ({This does not seem to offer full compensation for the exchange
as White is incompletely developed, but the alternative is even more dangerous:
} 12. Rc2 Rac8 13. a3 Rxc2 14. Qxc2 Rc8 15. Qd1 Bxd2+ 16. Qxd2 Qa2 17. e4 Qb1+
18. Qd1 Qxb2 19. Be2 Rc2 20. f3 Nc7 21. Bxc7 Rc1 {0-1 Nguyen,H (2406)-Wang,S 
(2187) Chengdu 2017}) 12... Qxb7 13. a3 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Rac8 15. f3 Rfd8 16. Kf2
Nc5 17. Qb4 Nd7 18. Bd3 e5 $15 19. dxe5 Nc5 20. Be2 Nd3+ 21. Bxd3 Rxd3 $19 {
Gusev,A (2400)-Smirnov,A (2396) Efremov 2017 (0-1, 32)}) 10... Nd7 $1 {Black
keeps developing, while preparing ...c7-c5 under favourable circumstances and
inviting White to finally take the pawn.} (10... Qa5+ 11. Nd2 c5 {runs into}
12. Rc3 $1 $146 {with big complications in which White has chances to retain
the initiative:} (12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Be5 Nd7 14. Bc3 Qc7 15. Bd3 {Goudriaan,E 
(2376)-Riemersma,L (2432) Amsterdam 2015 (В1/2-В1/2, 88)} Nb6 $11) 12... cxd4
13. Rc7 e5 14. Bg3 dxe3 15. fxe3 Bg5 16. Rxb7 Bxe3 17. Bc4 Nc6 18. Rf1 Rad8 19.
Rfxf7 Bxd2+ 20. Kf1 $40) 11. Rxc7 {The safest of the two possible captures.} (
11. Bxc7 Rac8 {leaves White a bit hanging:} 12. Be2 Qa5+ 13. Nd2 (13. Qd2 Bd8
$19 {leaves White pinned.} 14. b4 Qxa3) (13. Kf1 Nc5 14. dxc5 Rxc7 15. cxb6
Rxc1 16. Qxc1 Rc8 17. Qd1 Qxb6 $17) 13... Bxg2 14. Rg1 Bb7 $15) (11. Qa4 Rac8 (
11... Bd6 $5 {may be also good, but it requieres some accuracy:} 12. Bb5 Bxf4
13. Bxd7 Bd6 14. Bc6 Bxc6 15. Rxc6 {Jorczik,J (2326)-Klek,H (2311) Bayern 2015
(0-1, 35)} Qa2 16. Qc2 Qa1+ 17. Qc1 Qxc1+ 18. Rxc1 c5 $11) 12. Bb5 c6 13. Bc4
Qa5+ 14. Qxa5 bxa5 15. Ke2 c5 16. Bb5 Rfd8 17. Rhd1 a6 18. Bd3 a4 $11) 11...
Rac8 12. Rxc8 Rxc8 13. Bd3 Qa5+ 14. Kf1 Nf6 {At this height it may seem that
Black has just reasonable compensation for the pawn as White has a solid
structure. But the following lines show that things are not entirely so.} 15.
Kg1 (15. h3 Nd5 $17 16. Bg3 Bxa3 $1 {The structure is not as solid as it looks!
} 17. bxa3 Qxa3 18. Ne1 Rc1 19. Qd2 Qa1 20. e4 Rd1 21. Qe2 Nc3 22. Qe3 Rxd3 23.
Qxd3 Ba6 $19) 15... Nd5 16. Bg3 Bxa3 {Same idea.} 17. bxa3 Qxa3 18. Ne1 Rc1 19.
Qd2 Qa1 20. f3 Rd1 21. Qe2 Qc1 22. Bf2 Nc3 23. Qf1 a5 $17 {White is completely
