1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 {We now start investigating a series
of lines which can be classified as "The Exchange system" or else "The
Carlsbad structure". For White, it is optimal to develop his bishops on d3 and
f4 or g5, but due to the move order based on 3...Be7, he cannot achieve that
aim.} 5. Nf3 ({The main line goes} 5. Bf4 {and will be examined later.}) 5...
Nf6 6. Bg5 (6. Bf4 {transposes to 5.Bf4.}) ({Or if} 6. Qc2 {, preventing ...
Bf5 and hoping for Bf4, e2-e3 and Bd3,} c6 7. Bf4 (7. Bg5 g6 {transposes below}
) 7... g6 $1 {Same idea as in the main line.} 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3
Nbd7 $11 {White does not get much from} 11. Bh6 Ng4 12. Bg7 Rg8 13. Be5 Ngxe5
14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qc7 16. Qd4 Qb6 17. O-O O-O-O $11 {Arkell,K (2505)
-Dempsey,T Hastings 1995 (1-0, 49)}) 6... c6 {Preparing ...Bf5 without fearing
Qb3, which could be answered now with ...Qb6.} 7. Qc2 g6 $1 8. e4 {This way of
preventing Black from achieving a comfortable exchange system position was
introduced by Karpov. At this height of the theory, it is not dangerous for
Black. Staying within Black's improved exchange variation territory offers
very little:} (8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. e3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13.
b4 a6 14. a4 Nb6 15. b5 cxb5 16. axb5 a5 17. Na4 Nxa4 18. Rxa4 Qd6 19. Qb3 b6
$1 ({Better than} 19... Rfc8 20. Ne1 b6 21. Nd3 {when in anticipation of Nf4,
Black had to spend a tempo on relocating his rook.} Rd8 22. Rc1 Rac8 23. Raa1
$11 {Nei,I-Van Scheltinga,T Beverwijk 1966 (1/2-1/2, 50)}) 20. Ne1 Rac8 21. Nd3
Kg7 $17 {Black controls the open file and has a dangerous passed pawn.}) (8. e3
Bf5 9. Bd3 (9. Qb3 Qb6 {leads to an interesting situation. While Qxb6 ...axb6
followed by ...b6-b5 would just strengthen Black's structure, ...Qxb3 axb3
would weaken White's!} 10. Nd2 Nbd7 11. Be2 h6 12. Bf4 Qxb3 13. axb3 g5 14. Bg3
O-O 15. O-O Kg7 16. Rfc1 a6 17. f3 {Graf,A (2605)-Landa,K (2500)
Cappelle-la-Grande 1995 (0-1, 61)} Bg6 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gf7f5]} 18. h3 Rae8 19. Bc7
h5 20. e4 h4 $15) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rab1 Re8 (12... Ne4 {
may be premature:} 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Nxe4 Bf8 15. Bg5 dxe4 16. Bxd8 exd3 17. Bh4
c5 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Rfd1 {Kutueva, N (1961)-Vasenina,A (1750) Rybinsk 2009 
(1-0, 77) The far advanced pawn looks more like a weakness than strength.}) 13.
b4 a6 14. a4 Ne4 15. Bxe7 (15. Bf4 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Nb6 17. Qb3 Nc4 18. Ra1 Bd6 {
Hoping to get his knight to d6.} 19. Bh6 Qe7 20. b5 cxb5 21. axb5 a5 $15) 15...
Qxe7 16. Nd2 (16. b5 $2 axb5 17. axb5 Ra3 18. Rfc1 cxb5 $19 {De Carvalho,I 
(1878)-Umetsubo,C (2236) Maringa 2012 (0-1, 41)}) 16... Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Nb6 18.
b5 cxb5 19. axb5 a5 $15) 8... dxe4 $1 (8... Nxe4 9. Bxe7 $14 Qxe7 $2 10. Nxd5)
9. Bxf6 {The only consistent move.} (9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Be6 $15) 9... Bxf6
10. Qxe4+ Qe7 11. Bc4 Bf5 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. O-O-O Nd7 {Black's bishops are a
permanent threat for the enemy king and for the Isolani. This compensates for
the own king's (temporary) exposure.} 14. h3 (14. Rhe1+ {does not change
anything essentially:} Kf8 15. Ne4 Bxe4 16. Rxe4 Nb6 17. Bb3 Kg7 18. Ne5 Nd5
$11 {Korchagina,A (2167)-Kasaeva,S (1960) Moscow 2019 (1-0, 47)}) 14... Nb6 15.
Bb3 h5 16. Rhg1 ({Omitting this intermediate move offers Black additional
possibilities:} 16. Rhe1+ Kf8 17. Ne4 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 Kg7 19. Ne5 a5 $5 {As we
will see, the similar treatment is not entirely sound in the main line.} 20.
Nxf7 a4 21. Be6 Rhe8 22. Nd6 Re7 23. b3 Rd8 24. Nc4 axb3 25. axb3 (25. Nxb6
bxa2 26. Kb2 Rd6 27. Bf5 Rxe4 28. Bxe4 Rxd4 29. Rxd4 Bxd4+ 30. Kxa2 Bxb6 {
, and since there is no obvious way to force the pawn to advance on dark
squares with Bc8, Black is not without winning chances.}) 25... Nxc4 26. bxc4
Rxd4 27. Rdxd4 Bxd4 28. Rxd4 Rxe6 29. Rd7+ Kf6 30. Rxb7 Re4 $11) 16... h4 17.
Rge1+ Kf8 18. Ne4 {The only way to display activity.} (18. Ne5 $2 Bg5+) (18. d5
cxd5 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8] followed by Rc8, putting the enemy king in danger.})
18... Bxe4 19. Rxe4 Kg7 20. Ne5 Nd5 (20... a5 $6 21. Nxf7 a4 22. Be6 Rhe8 23.
Nd6 Re7 {allows} 24. Bg4 $14 {, which was not available in the similar line
above.}) (20... Rhf8 $5 21. Kb1 a5 22. a3 a4 23. Ba2 Rae8 24. Rde1 Nc8 25. Nd7
Rxe4 26. Rxe4 Nd6 27. Nxf6 Kxf6 28. Rxh4 Re8 29. Rf4+ Kg7 30. Kc1 Re2 $44) 21.
Bxd5 cxd5 22. Re2 Rac8+ 23. Kd2 Rh5 24. Nf3 Rf5 25. Kd3 Rf4 $11 {Sulava,N 
(2565)-Brkic,A (2564) Marija Bistrica 2011 (0-1, 47)} *

