1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 {This is the main line in the
Carlsbad structure with the given move order.} ({Just a few words about the
plans based on} 5. g3 {In the Carlsbad structure the bishop does not belong to
g2. It fails to support b4-b5, it leaves the c4-square weak after b2-b4 and it
is restricted by the black central chain.} Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 c6 8. O-O ({
Preventing ...Bf5 with} 8. Qc2 {does not really bother Black.} Re8 9. O-O Nbd7
10. Bf4 Nf8 11. Rad1 Ng6 12. Bc1 Bd6 13. Rfe1 h6 14. a3 a5 {possibly followed
by ...Ne7 and ...Bf5.}) 8... Bf5 9. Nh4 $5 (9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. Bxe5
Nd7 12. Bf4 Nb6 13. b3 Qd7 14. a4 a5 15. Qd2 $15 {1/2-1/2 Tempone,M (2450)
-Ricardi,P (2415) Buenos Aires 1988. It is only Black who can think of active
kingside operations.} Rfe8) 9... Be6 10. Qc2 (10. f4 Re8 11. Qd3 c5 12. dxc5
Na6) 10... Qc8 11. Bg5 Re8 $11) 5... Nf6 ({The main alternative is} 5... c6 6.
e3 Bf5 {, but this exposes the bishop to} 7. g4 Be6 8. h4) 6. Qc2 {An early
attempt to prevent ...Bf5. But this implies a strong commitment, allowing
Black to start strong counterplay in the centre.} ({The main continuation} 6.
e3 {is examined below}) 6... c5 $1 7. dxc5 (7. e3 {leads to a symmetrical
structure where once again the queen is not optimally placed.} cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6
(8... O-O $5) 9. Bb5 (9. Nf3 O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Gc8g4] Planning ...Re8 or ...Bg4.
} 10. Bb5 Nb4 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 11. Qb1 Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Nc2+ 14. Qxc2
Qa5+ 15. Nd2 Qxb5 $15 {With ample compensation for the pawn, as the white king
is stuck in the centre.}) 9... Qb6 10. Nge2 O-O 11. Bxc6 Qxc6 12. O-O Be6 $11 {
Foisor,S (2320)-Zatonskih,A (2462) Saint Louis 2009 (0-1, 56).}) (7. Nf3 Nc6 8.
dxc5 (8. e3 {as played in Alonso Rosell,A (2393)-Prohaszka,P (2508) Herceg
Novi 2008 (0-1, 86) may transpose after an exchange on d4, but Black could try
to take over the initiative:} Nb4 9. Qb1 {Preventing ...Bf5.} c4 10. a3 Nc6 11.
Be2 O-O 12. O-O a6 $11 {, followed by ...b7-b5.}) 8... Bxc5 (8... d4 $5 9.
O-O-O O-O 10. Nb5 Qa5 11. Nfxd4 Qxa2 12. e3 Qa1+ 13. Qb1 Qxb1+ 14. Kxb1 Bxc5
$11) 9. e3 O-O 10. Rd1 d4 11. Be2 Qb6 12. Na4 $6 (12. exd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4
14. O-O $11) 12... Qb4+ 13. Kf1 dxe3 $1 {Attacking the bishop on f4.} 14. fxe3
Be7 $15 {Karason,A (2250)-Arnason,A Reykjavik 1990 (1/2-1/2, 25)}) 7... d4 8.
O-O-O {It is hard to decide whether the king is safer in the centre or on the
queenside.} (8. Rd1 {D'Costa,L (2157)-Stephenson,F (2241) Millfield 2000 (0-1,
15)} Bxc5 9. e3 Qe7 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Na4 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 Bd7 13. a3 O-O $1 {
A promising piece sacrifice.} 14. Nf3 (14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. axb4 Bb5+ 16. Ne2 Rac8
17. Qb3 Nh5 18. Bg3 Rfe8 $5 $19 {The knight is out of play on a4 and the
central pressure is killing.}) (14. axb4 Nxb4 15. Qe2 d3 16. Bxd3 Bxa4 17. Bd6
Qd7 18. Bxb4 Bxd1 19. Qxd1 Rfd8 20. Ke2 Qg4+ 21. Nf3 Qxb4 $19) 14... Rfd8 15.
exd4 Ba5 16. Nc3 Rac8 $15 {With more than enough compensation for the pawn, as
Black is fully mobilized while White is still struggling to connect his rooks.}
) 8... Qa5 (8... Bxc5 $5 9. e3 O-O 10. exd4 Bd6 {offers Black good
compensation for the pawn, as the white king is a bit insecure.}) 9. Qa4+ (9.
Rxd4 {is better, offering White chances to maintain equality.} Nc6 10. e3 $5 (
10. Rd2 $2 Nb4 11. Qb1 Be6 $17) (10. Rd1 Nb4 11. Qa4+ Qxa4 12. Nxa4 Nxa2+ 13.
Kb1 Nb4 14. f3 Be6 15. e4 O-O 16. Nc3 Bxc5 $15) (10. Ra4 Qxc5 11. e3 {
transposes}) 10... Qxc5 (10... Nxd4 11. exd4 {strengthens White's centre.}) 11.
