[ECO "D37"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[EventDate "2019.??.??"]

1. d4 ({It is interesting to compare a sub-line from the comment to the 6th
move with this one:} 1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nf3
Bb4 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O {In this position Black usually
retreats with the bishop to e7 (sometimes after a2-a3, which is useful as it
prevents ...Nb4.) In the line below the bishop is on e7 already.}) 1... d5 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Qc2 $5 {This is intended to be a subtle
semi-waiting move. White takes the b1-h7 diagonal under control in advance,
hoping to transpose to a normal Exchange variation. But the queen's early
development weakens the control in the centre, allowing an immediate reaction.}
c5 $1 ({White's idea would be justified after} 5... O-O 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 c6
8. e3 {followed by Bd3.}) 6. cxd5 ({If} 6. e3 {I would recommend} b6 $5 $146 (
6... cxd4 7. exd4 O-O 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Be2 Nc6 {leads to an improved version of
the tabiya mentioned in the introduction.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bb5+ {Otherwise
Black would get a comfortable hanging pawns version, as the queen is exposed
on c2 and the bishop passive on c1.} Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 (9... Qxd7 $5 {leads
to interesting but unnecessary complications:} 10. Ne5 Qe6 11. Qa4+ Nbd7 12.
O-O O-O 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. e4 dxe4 15. d5 Qf5 16. f3 Ne5 17. fxe4 Qg6 {with
mutual chances.}) 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 Rc8 $11) (6. dxc5 {is examined in the
next line.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 (7. Qa4+ {mainly helps Black to develop.} Bd7 8.
Qxd4 exd5 9. Nxd5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Qd1 O-O-O {The quickest way to set up
pressure along the central files, but also slightly exposing his own king. The
following game is illustrative for the strength of Black's initiative:} (11...
O-O 12. Bd2 Rfd8 {also offers Black the initiative.}) 12. Bd2 Bg4 13. e3 Rd7
14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Rhd8 16. Rd1 Qb4 17. Bb5 (17. Ba6 Kb8) 17... Rxd2 18. Rxd2
Rxd2 19. Kxd2 Qxb2+ 20. Kd1 Qxc3 21. Qf5+ Kc7 22. Qb1 Bb4 23. Qc1 Ne4 24. Rf1
a6 {0-1 Ovsejevitsch,S (2600)-Fodor,T (2420) Zalakaros 2010}) 7... O-O {
This is possible precisely because the queen is not on d1 anymore.} 8. Bg5 {
The most active move and the safest way to stay out of trouble.} (8. a3 Nxd5 (
8... exd5 $5 {leads to an interesting isolani version. Qc2 and a2-a3 do not
count as useful developing moves.}) 9. Nf3 (9. Bd2 b6 10. e4 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Bb7
12. Be2 Qc7 13. O-O Nd7 $11) 9... Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Bf6 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. e3 {
Hahn,A (2218)-Bennett,A (2306) Seattle 2003 (0-1, 41)} Na6 $17 13. Bxa6 Qa5+
14. Qd2 Qxa6 15. Qxd7 $2 Rfd8 16. Qc7 Rac8 17. Qg3 Rc2 18. Bd2 Bxb2 19. Rd1 Qd3
$19) (8. e3 {is too passive to be challenging.} exd5 9. Bd3 Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6
11. O-O Bd6 $11 12. e4 Re8 13. f4 $2 Ng4 (13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Ba6
16. Rd1 h6 17. Bf3 Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Rad8 $11 {Zhou,J (2650)-Xu,J (2513) China 2010
(В1/2-В1/2, 45)}) 14. g3 Bc5+ 15. Kg2 Qd7 16. f5 Ne5 $17) (8. g3 $6 {weakens
the long diagonal.} Nxd5 $15 9. Nb3 (9. Bg2 $2 Nb4 10. Qd1 Qxd4 $19) (9. Nxd5
Qxd5 10. Nf3 e5 $15) 9... Nxc3 10. Qxc3 (10. bxc3 Qd5 $15) 10... Nc6 11. Bd2
Qd5 $15) (8. e4 $146 {is a premature display of activity.} exd5 9. e5 Ng4 10.
Bf4 (10. f4 $2 Bc5 $19) 10... Bg5 11. Bxg5 Qxg5 12. Nf3 Qh5 13. Nxd5 Nxe5 {
Black has some initiative in a symmetrical position.} 14. Be2 Bg4 15. O-O-O
Nbc6 16. Nxe5 Bxe2 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Rd2 Bg4 20. f3 Be6 $15 {
The knight is almost trapped as taking on c6 would get into a nasty pin and
both white wings are under pressure.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 (9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. e3 exd5
{This position is similar to the one arising in Line 13 from the first
database, with the difference that the queen stands on the more exposed
c2-square and not on the safer d2-square.} 11. Be2 ({With the queen on d2,
Line 13 from the first database goes} 11. Bb5 {But here Black is doing well
after} a6 12. Ba4 b5 13. Bb3 Bxd4 14. exd4 {Here is the first difference: the
queen does not control d4.} Re8+ 15. Ne2 a5 {And now the queen stands in the
bishop's way.} 16. Qd2 Bf5 $11) (11. Rd1 Nc6 12. Be2 Nxd4 13. exd4 Be6 $15)
11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. O-O Be5 14. Na4 Qd6 15. g3 Bh3 16. Rfd1 Rac8 17.
Rac1 Qf6 18. b3 Rfe8 $11 19. Nc5 (19. Rd2 $2 d4 20. e4 Bf4 $1 $17 {Tomaszewski,
R (2435)-Boensch,U (2530) Halle 1987 (0-1, 39)}) 19... a5 (19... d4 $11) 20.
Bf1 Bg4 21. Rd2 h5 $11) 9... Nxd5 10. Bxe7 (10. Nxd5 $2 Bxh4 $19 {leaves the
knights hanging.}) 10... Qxe7 {The most active continuation.} ({Black has all
the reasons to count on dull equality after} 10... Nxe7 11. Rd1 Qb6 12. e3 (12.
Qb3 Qxb3 13. Nxb3 {1/2-1/2 Erdos,V (2576)-Khalifman,A (2628) Plovdiv 2008})
12... e5 13. Nf3 Bf5 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Rxd3 Qg6 16. Nh4 Qg4 {1/2-1/2 Golod,V 
(2590)-David, A (2487) Vlissingen 2000} 17. g3 Nbc6 18. O-O g5 19. Ng2 Qe6 $11)
11. Nxd5 exd5 12. e3 Nc6 {Black's lead in development compensates for White's
blockade on d4. Once again we notice that the queen does not defend the centre.
} 13. Qd2 {Practically a loss of time, but optically the safest move.} (13. Rd1
{offers Black some light initiative.} Bg4 14. Nxc6 (14. Be2 Nxd4 15. Rxd4 Rac8
16. Qd2 Bxe2 17. Kxe2 Qg5 18. g3 Qh5+ 19. f3 Qg6 20. Rc1 Qa6+ {followed by ...
Qxa2.}) 14... bxc6 15. Be2 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 f5 17. O-O f4 18. Qf3 fxe3 19. Qxe3
Qxe3 20. fxe3 Rab8 21. b3 Rb6 22. Rxf8+ Kxf8 23. e4 Ra6 24. exd5 cxd5 25. Rxd5
{В1/2-В1/2 Akopian,V (2679)-Jakovenko,D (2737) Elista 2008}) (13. Nxc6 bxc6 14.
Rd1 (14. Qxc6 d4 $17 {[%cal Ge7b4,Gc8b7]} 15. Qxa8 Qb4+) 14... Be6 15. Be2 {
1/2-1/2 Villar Reymundo,J (2233)-Panelo Munoz,M (2379) Almazan 2017} c5 $11)
13... Nxd4 {A rather simplistic continuation.} (13... Re8 $1 {is much stronger.
At a later moment the pressure along the e-file will prove useful.} 14. Bb5 ({
The point is that} 14. Be2 {runs into the double attack} Qe4 $15 15. Bf3 $2
Qxd4 $1) 14... Bd7 15. Bxc6 (15. O-O Nxd4 16. Bxd7 Nf3+ 17. gxf3 Qxd7 $15)
15... bxc6 16. Nb3 c5 $11 17. Qxd5 $6 Bb5 18. O-O-O Rad8 19. Qf5 Bd3 20. Rxd3
g6 $17) 14. Qxd4 Qe4 15. Bd3 (15. Qxe4 dxe4 16. Bc4 {offers White just a
symbolic advantage.} Rd8 17. O-O (17. Ke2 Bg4+ 18. f3 Rac8 19. Bb3 exf3+ 20.
gxf3 Be6 $15) 17... Kf8 18. Rfd1 Bg4 19. Rdc1 Rac8 20. h3 Bd7 21. Bd5 Rxc1+ 22.
Rxc1 Bxh3 23. Bxb7 Be6 24. Bxe4 Bxa2 25. Ra1 Be6 26. Rxa7 Rd1+ 27. Kh2 Rd2 $11)
15... Qxd4 (15... Qxg2 $6 16. O-O-O Qg4 17. f4 Qe6 18. Rhg1 f6 19. Kb1 {
with some initiative for the pawn in Bratanov,Z (2457)-Doncea,V (2388) Sunny
Beach 2011 (0-1, 54)}) 16. exd4 Re8+ 17. Kd2 Kf8 $11 {Black should have no
problems reaching a draw, as he only has one potential weakness on d5.} *

