1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Qc2 c5 6. dxc5 {An ambitious, but
in view of Black's answer also risky move.} d4 $1 {Black refrains from
retrieving the pawn and prefers to gain space in the centre. This implies a
pawn sacrifice, but quite a promising one, as White will have problems with
his development.} 7. Nb5 {This forces Black to sacrifice a pawn:} (7. Na4 {
places the knight on a bad square.} b6 $1 {Inviting White to clear the a3-f8
diagonal and give up his queenside space advantage.} (7... Nc6 8. a3 e5 9. e4
Nxe4 $6 ({Better is} 9... Bg4 10. Be2 b6 $44 {but it is probably best to
switch to this plan at once, as in the mainline.}) 10. Qxe4 Qa5+ 11. b4 Qxa4
12. Be2 $1 (12. Bd3 {exposes the bishop to} f5 {Miles,A (2565)-Van der Sterren,
P (2520) Wijk aan Zee 1987 (0-1, 35)}) 12... Nxb4 13. O-O Nc6 14. Nxe5 $14) 8.
cxb6 (8. e4 bxc5 {retrieves the pawn and consolidates Black's space advantage.}
9. Bd3 Nc6 10. a3 e5 11. O-O O-O 12. Bd2 Bg4 13. Ne1 Qc7 14. f3 Be6 $17 {
Krasenkow,M (2585)-Nielsen,P (2636) Copenhagen 2003 (0-1, 40)}) 8... axb6 9. b3
Bb7 10. e3 e5 11. Nxe5 ({What else? if} 11. Be2 d3 $1 12. Qxd3 Qxd3 13. Bxd3 e4
{wins a piece.}) (11. exd4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nc6 $1 {offers Black tremendous
initiative. For instance:} 13. dxe5 Bb4+ 14. Bd2 Nd4 15. Qd3 Nxf3+ 16. Ke2
Qxd3+ 17. Kxd3 O-O-O+ 18. Ke3 Nxd2 19. exf6 Rhe8+ $17) 11... dxe3 12. fxe3 (12.
Bxe3 Bb4+ $17 13. Bd2 $2 Qd4 $19 14. Bc3 Qxe5+) 12... O-O 13. Bd3 Qc7 14. Bb2
Bb4+ 15. Kf1 Re8 {with promising initiative for the pawn.}) (7. Ne4 Nxe4 8.
Qxe4 {exposes the white queen.} Nc6 9. a3 (9. g4 $1 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qxc5 $15) 9...
a5 (9... f5 10. Qf4 O-O 11. b4 b6 12. cxb6 axb6 13. Bb2 Bf6 14. Rd1 e5 $15) 10.
g3 (10. g4 Bxc5 $11) 10... O-O 11. Bg2 Bxc5 12. O-O f5 13. Qf4 Qf6 14. e4 e5
$17 {Van Hoolandt,P (2065)-Upper,J (1969) Quebec 2018 (0-1, 40)}) 7... e5 $1 {
It is essential to keep the molesting pawn on d4.} 8. Nxe5 (8. e3 Nc6 9. exd4
exd4 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Bc7 (11. Nd6 Nh5 $17) (11. Bd6 Bxd6 12. cxd6 Qa5+ 13. Qd2
Re8+ 14. Kd1 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Ne4+ 16. Kc1 Nxf2 $17) 11... Qd7 12. Ne5 Qe6 13.
O-O-O Ne8 14. f4 {Svidler,P (2744)-Jakovenko,D (2729) Sochi 2012 (0-1, 25)}
Bxc5 15. Nd3 b6 $19) 8... a6 9. Na3 (9. Nd6+ Bxd6 10. cxd6 Qa5+ 11. Qd2 Qxe5
$19 {Zhu,C (2485)-Zatonskih,A (2522) Hangzhou 2011 (1/2-1/2, 53)}) (9. Qa4 O-O
10. Nd6 Bxd6 11. cxd6 Qxd6 12. Nd3 Bf5 13. Bf4 Qe6 14. Qa3 Qxc4 $15 {В1/2-В1/2
Bogner,S (2522)-Naumann,A (2528) Bad Liebenzell 2010}) 9... O-O {White's
knight on a3 is passive and he needs a lot of time to complete his development.
} 10. g3 (10. Nd3 Bf5 11. g3 Nfd7 ({A better regrouping than} 11... Nbd7 12.
Bg2 Nxc5 {which also offers Black reasonable compensation:} 13. O-O Rc8 14. Qd1
Re8 15. Bf4 Qb6 16. Rb1 Nfe4 17. Be5 {Shimanov,A (2606)-Tregubov,P (2595)
Konya 2012 (1-0, 34)} Nd7 18. Bf4 Bxa3 19. bxa3 Qf6 20. Bd2 Ndc5 $15) 12. Bg2
Nxc5 13. O-O Nc6 14. Qd1 Nxd3 15. exd3 Nb4 16. Bxb7 (16. Be4 Bxe4 17. dxe4 Re8
18. Bd2 Nc6 19. Nc2 Bf8 20. Re1 Qd7 $15) 16... Bxd3 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Re1 Be4
19. Qe2 (19. Qxd4 Bh1 20. f3 Qxf3 21. Qf2 Qxf2+ 22. Kxf2 Nd3+ 23. Kg1 Nxe1 24.
Kxh1 Re8 25. Bd2 Nd3 $15 {with a persistent initiative in the ending}) 19... f5
20. f3 Bc5 21. Kg2 d3 $36 {with a dangerous initiative.}) (10. Bd2 Bxc5 11. b4
Re8 12. Nd3 Bf8 13. c5 {Bosboom,M (2440)-Dutreeuw,M (2315) Germany 2003 (1-0,
40)} a5 14. bxa5 Bf5 15. Nc4 Na6 $19) 10... Qa5+ 11. Bd2 (11. Qd2 Qxc5 12. Nd3
Qc6 $15) 11... Qxc5 12. Nd3 {Under different circumstances such a blocking
knight would ensure White against any problems. But due to his delayed
development, White is in a critical position anyway. One important aspect is
that the knight is excposed to ...Bxd3 followed by ...Ne5, removing the
blockade.} Qc6 13. Rg1 (13. f3 Bf5 $15) 13... Bf5 14. Bg2 Qc8 15. c5 (15. Qb3
Nc6 16. c5 Re8 17. Rc1 {Markus,R (2481)-Benkovic,P (2469) Subotica 2003 (1-0,
62)} Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Ne5 19. Qxd4 Bxc5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 20. Rxc5 (20. Qc3 Qf5 $19)
20... Qxc5 21. Qxc5 Nd3+ 22. Kd1 Nxc5 $17) 15... Nbd7 16. c6 (16. b4 Re8 17.
Kf1 a5 $15) 16... Bxa3 17. bxa3 Ne5 18. Nxe5 Bxc2 19. cxb7 Qe6 20. bxa8=Q Rxa8
21. Bxa8 Qxe5 $15 {Khalifman,A (2688)-Topalov,V (2739) Dubai 2002 (0-1, 32)} *

